---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Hydronic Ceiling Panels | EES"
  description="Suspended hydronic ceiling tiles for radiant heating and cooling — modular, efficient, and designed for standard Australian ceiling grids."
>
  <!-- Page Header -->
  <section class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <h1>Hydronic Ceiling Panels</h1>
      <p>Heating, cooling, and a finished ceiling — in one system.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Product Hero -->
  <section class="product-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero-layout">
        <div class="hero-image">
          <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Final_webp/639607_dee5110879914401aa781f84eeb92cdc_mv2.webp" alt="3D render of a hydronic ceiling panel showing the three layers — insulation barrier, capillary tube mat, and architectural finish surface" />
        </div>
        <div class="hero-text">
          <p class="section-label">The Technology</p>
          <h2>Three Functions in One Tile</h2>
          <p>Our suspended hydronic ceiling tiles are modular and versatile. They are capable of both heating and cooling and are designed to accept a range of finishing surfaces. Easy to install. Simple to operate.</p>
          <div class="three-layers">
            <div class="layer">
              <span class="layer-number">1</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Insulative Barrier</strong>
                <p>Directly opposite to where the conditioning occurs — keeping energy where it's needed.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="layer">
              <span class="layer-number">2</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Capillary Tube Mat</strong>
                <p>A highly responsive conditioning system embedded within the tile itself.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="layer">
              <span class="layer-number">3</span>
              <div>
                <strong>Architectural Finish</strong>
                <p>The room-facing surface — choose the material that suits your interior.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Panel Close-Ups -->
  <section class="section panel-closeups">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="closeup-grid">
        <div class="closeup-card">
          <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/IMG_7483.webp" alt="Blue polypropylene capillary tube mat bonded to foil-faced insulation panel — the active conditioning layer of each tile" />
          <div class="closeup-text">
            <h3>The Capillary Tube Mat</h3>
            <p>Polypropylene tubes at tight spacing bonded directly to the insulation. Water circulates through these tubes to heat or cool the panel surface uniformly — no hot or cold spots.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="closeup-card">
          <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Final_webp/IMG_0030.webp" alt="Rear view of a completed hydronic ceiling panel showing capillary tubes bonded to foil insulation with connecting hoses" />
          <div class="closeup-text">
            <h3>Panel Assembly</h3>
            <p>Each 600 × 1200mm tile is assembled in-house — capillary mat bonded to insulation, pressure tested, then fitted with the chosen architectural finish before delivery.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="closeup-card">
          <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Final_webp/IMG_0041.webp" alt="Finished face of a hydronic ceiling panel with perforated metal surface — clean, architectural appearance that conceals the system" />
          <div class="closeup-text">
            <h3>The Finished Face</h3>
            <p>From the room below, all you see is a clean ceiling tile. The conditioning system is completely concealed — invisible to occupants.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Why Ceiling? -->
  <div class="why-ceiling-group">
    <div class="diagonal-divider" style="background: #fff;">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 1440 120" preserveAspectRatio="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
        <polygon points="0,0 0,120 1440,120" fill="#0E2B47" />
      </svg>
    </div>

    <section class="why-ceiling">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="why-layout">
          <div class="why-text">
            <p class="section-label section-label--light">Why the Ceiling?</p>
            <h2>The Most Effective Radiant Surface</h2>
            <p>The human body exchanges energy with its environment through three mechanisms: <strong>radiation</strong>, <strong>convection</strong>, and <strong>exhalation</strong>. Radiant transfer has the greatest impact on comfort.</p>
            <p>Radiant systems deliver both radiant and convective energy transfer simultaneously. They are healthier, more comfortable, and operate at roughly <strong>one-third the cost</strong> of conventional systems.</p>
            <div class="why-points">
              <div class="why-point">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none"><path d="M5 10l3.5 3.5L15 7" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
                <span><strong>Uninterrupted surface</strong> — no furniture or foot traffic in the way</span>
              </div>
              <div class="why-point">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none"><path d="M5 10l3.5 3.5L15 7" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
                <span><strong>Doesn't activate dust</strong> that accumulates on floors</span>
              </div>
              <div class="why-point">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none"><path d="M5 10l3.5 3.5L15 7" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
                <span>Far more <strong>hygienic</strong> than floor conditioning or forced-air systems</span>
              </div>
              <div class="why-point">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none"><path d="M5 10l3.5 3.5L15 7" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
                <span><strong>Uniform MRT</strong> across the occupied zone at any distance</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="why-image">
            <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/mounting.webp" alt="Comparison diagram of four radiant conditioning approaches — floor heating (A), ceiling heating and cooling (B and D), and wall heating (C) — showing coverage, distance uniformity, and furniture obstruction" />
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="diagonal-divider" style="background: #0E2B47;">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 1440 120" preserveAspectRatio="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
        <polygon points="0,0 0,120 1440,120" fill="#fff" />
      </svg>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Ceiling Surface Options -->
  <section class="section surface-options">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <p class="section-label">Finishing Surfaces</p>
        <h2>One System, <span class="h2-light">Many Finishes</span></h2>
        <p class="section-desc">The same hydronic capillary tube system accepts a range of architectural finishes. Choose the surface that suits your space.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="surface-showcase">
        <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/ceiling-panels-labeled.webp" alt="TestCell ceiling divided into bays with five different architectural finishes — adhesive vinyl coated wallpaper, rendered coating, perforated metal panel, mini-orb, and plasterboard with vinyl finish" />
      </div>

      <div class="surface-grid">
        <div class="surface-card">
          <h3>Perforated Metal</h3>
          <p>Clean, modern appearance with excellent radiant transfer. Suitable for commercial and architectural applications.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="surface-card">
          <h3>Plasterboard with Vinyl</h3>
          <p>Standard ceiling appearance. Blends seamlessly with conventional suspended ceilings — ideal for retrofits.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="surface-card">
          <h3>Rendered Coating</h3>
          <p>Textured, solid finish. Good acoustic properties and a premium architectural look.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="surface-card">
          <h3>Mini-Orb</h3>
          <p>Corrugated metal profile. Industrial aesthetic with good structural rigidity and airflow characteristics.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="surface-card">
          <h3>Vinyl Coated Wallpaper</h3>
          <p>Adhesive-applied finish. Lightweight, cost-effective, and available in a wide range of colours and textures.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Installed Ceiling -->
  <section class="section installed-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="installed-layout">
        <div class="installed-image">
          <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/IMG_7977.webp" alt="Looking up at the installed hydronic ceiling panels from inside the TestCell — blue capillary tubes visible through the grid before finishing surfaces are applied" />
        </div>
        <div class="installed-text">
          <p class="section-label">Installation</p>
          <h2>Standard Grid, Simple Install</h2>
          <p>Each panel is sized at <strong>600 × 1200mm</strong> to fit standard Australian suspended ceiling grids. Panels drop in like conventional ceiling tiles — no specialist tools, no custom framing.</p>
          <p>Water connections between panels use quick-connect fittings. A single manifold feeds all panels in a zone, with individual flow meters for balancing and monitoring.</p>
          <p>The modular design means panels can be removed individually for maintenance or access to services above, without disturbing the rest of the ceiling.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Thermal Performance -->
  <section class="section thermal-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <p class="section-label">Proven Performance</p>
        <h2>Thermal Imaging <span class="h2-light">Results</span></h2>
        <p class="section-desc">Tested in our purpose-built simulation room. Thermal imaging confirms uniform surface temperature distribution in both heating and cooling modes.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="thermal-comparison">
        <div class="thermal-card">
          <div class="thermal-img-wrap">
            <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/thermal-heating-full.webp" alt="Thermal image of ceiling panels in heating mode — uniform warm surface temperatures at 27.6°C shown in red and orange" />
          </div>
          <div class="thermal-info">
            <span class="thermal-mode thermal-mode--heat">Heating Mode — 27.6°C</span>
            <p>Even red/orange distribution confirms uniform heat delivery across all panel surfaces. No cold spots at joints or edges.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="thermal-card">
          <div class="thermal-img-wrap">
            <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/thermal-cooling-full.webp" alt="Thermal image of ceiling panels in cooling mode — uniform cool surface temperatures at 14.4°C shown in blue and green" />
          </div>
          <div class="thermal-info">
            <span class="thermal-mode thermal-mode--cool">Cooling Mode — 14.4°C</span>
            <p>Blue thermal signature shows effective, uniform cooling across all panels. No warm spots or condensation risk at these operating temperatures.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="thermal-link">
        <p>Full testing methodology and instrumentation details are available on our <a href="/laboratory/test-room">Simulation Test Room</a> page.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- System Components -->
  <section class="section components-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <p class="section-label">System Architecture</p>
        <h2>How It <span class="h2-light">All Connects</span></h2>
        <p class="section-desc">The hydronic system uses modular, low-voltage components. A heat pump circulates temperature-controlled water through the ceiling panels via a central manifold.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="system-hero">
        <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Final_webp/test-hydronic-2-230616.webp" alt="3D isometric view of the complete hydronic ceiling system showing ceiling panels with hot and cold piping loops, mixing station, and equipment cabinet" />
      </div>

      <div class="components-grid">
        <div class="component-card">
          <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/diagram.webp" alt="System schematic showing heat pump, water tank, pressure tank, vacuum relief valve, circulation pump and capillary tube mat connections" />
          <div class="component-text">
            <h3>System Schematic</h3>
            <p>Heat pump drives water through the heat exchanger into the capillary tube mats via the circulation pump. Pressure tanks and vacuum relief valves ensure stable, safe operation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="component-card">
          <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/plumbing-full.webp" alt="Assembled hydronic plumbing manifold with 24V DC pumps, switching actuators, mixing valves and pressure tanks" />
          <div class="component-text">
            <h3>Hydraulic Manifold</h3>
            <p>PPR piping with brass fittings. Each circuit has its own flow meter and switching actuator for zone-by-zone control. All components run on 24V DC for safety.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="component-card">
          <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/IMG_6357.webp" alt="Close-up of the hydronic manifold showing individual circuit flow meters, isolation valves and pipe connections" />
          <div class="component-text">
            <h3>Flow Control</h3>
            <p>Individual flow meters on each circuit allow precise monitoring and balancing. The system can be tuned panel-by-panel to match the thermal load of each zone.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="specs-bar">
        <div class="spec-item">
          <span class="spec-value">40–85W</span>
          <span class="spec-name">Circulation Pumps</span>
          <span class="spec-detail">Variable speed, 24V DC — each serves 20–40m²</span>
        </div>
        <div class="spec-item">
          <span class="spec-value">24V DC</span>
          <span class="spec-name">Switching Actuators</span>
          <span class="spec-detail">For hot and cold tank selection</span>
        </div>
        <div class="spec-item">
          <span class="spec-value">600 × 1200mm</span>
          <span class="spec-name">Panel Size</span>
          <span class="spec-detail">Fits standard Australian suspended ceiling grids</span>
        </div>
        <div class="spec-item">
          <span class="spec-value">PPR</span>
          <span class="spec-name">Piping</span>
          <span class="spec-detail">With brass fittings — modular and serviceable</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Development Story -->
  <section class="section dev-story">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <p class="section-label">Design &amp; Development</p>
        <h2>How We Built <span class="h2-light">the Panels</span></h2>
        <p class="section-desc">From insulation cutting to pressure testing — every panel is designed, assembled and validated in-house at our Geelong facility.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline">
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">
            <span class="timeline-number">1</span>
            <div class="timeline-line"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <div class="timeline-images">
              <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/IMG-4164.webp" alt="CNC router cutting foil-faced insulation panels to size on a vertical Multicam machine" loading="lazy" />
            </div>
            <h3>Insulation Panel Cutting</h3>
            <p>Foil-faced insulation boards are CNC-cut to precise 600 × 1200mm dimensions. The insulation forms the back of each tile — an insulative barrier that keeps radiant energy directed into the room.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">
            <span class="timeline-number">2</span>
            <div class="timeline-line"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <div class="timeline-images timeline-images--double">
              <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/191330305_1530368173988011_309953162325682046_n.webp" alt="Close-up of blue polypropylene capillary tube mat being positioned on an insulation panel" loading="lazy" />
              <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/Mats.webp" alt="Capillary tube mats prepared and laid out ready for bonding to insulation panels" loading="lazy" />
            </div>
            <h3>Capillary Tube Mat Bonding</h3>
            <p>Polypropylene capillary tube mats are bonded directly to the insulation surface. The tight tube spacing ensures uniform heat distribution — no hot or cold spots across the panel face.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">
            <span class="timeline-number">3</span>
            <div class="timeline-line"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <div class="timeline-images timeline-images--triple">
              <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/IMG_0046.webp" alt="Completed panel showing capillary tubes bonded to foil insulation — front view in workshop" loading="lazy" />
              <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/IMG_0048.webp" alt="Panel standing upright showing the full capillary tube pattern and insulation backing" loading="lazy" />
              <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/IMG_0049.webp" alt="Angled view of the completed panel showing tube density and insulation edge detail" loading="lazy" />
            </div>
            <h3>Panel Assembly &amp; Inspection</h3>
            <p>Each panel is assembled, visually inspected for tube spacing consistency, and pressure tested before the architectural finish is applied. Any panel that doesn't meet spec is rejected.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">
            <span class="timeline-number">4</span>
            <div class="timeline-line"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <div class="timeline-images timeline-images--double">
              <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/1.webp" alt="Multiple ceiling panels plumbed together on a workbench for system testing before installation" loading="lazy" />
              <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/IMG_6357.webp" alt="Hydronic manifold with flow meters connected to individual panel circuits for flow balancing" loading="lazy" />
            </div>
            <h3>Plumbing &amp; Flow Testing</h3>
            <p>Panels are connected to the manifold and flow-tested as a complete system. Individual flow meters on each circuit allow precise balancing before the ceiling is installed.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">
            <span class="timeline-number">5</span>
            <div class="timeline-line"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <div class="timeline-images timeline-images--double">
              <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/IMG_7797.webp" alt="Hydronic ceiling panels installed in the TestCell ceiling grid — blue capillary tubes visible from below before finishing surfaces are applied" loading="lazy" />
              <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/IMG_7910.webp" alt="Finished ceiling inside the TestCell with panels installed and material samples displayed on the surface" loading="lazy" />
            </div>
            <h3>Ceiling Installation</h3>
            <p>Panels drop into standard 600 × 1200mm suspended ceiling grids. Water connections between panels use quick-connect fittings — no soldering, no specialist tools required on site.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">
            <span class="timeline-number">6</span>
          </div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <div class="timeline-images">
              <img src="/image/WIP/TestRoom_Development_webp/IMG_7928.webp" alt="Researcher monitoring data inside the completed TestCell — hydronic ceiling panels active overhead with instrumentation recording thermal performance" loading="lazy" />
            </div>
            <h3>Testing &amp; Validation</h3>
            <p>Every panel configuration is tested in our purpose-built simulation room under real-world conditions — thermal imaging, comfort carts and continuous data logging confirm performance before any system ships.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="section cta-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="cta-box">
        <h2>Interested in hydronic ceiling panels?</h2>
        <p>We work with architects, engineers and building professionals to design radiant ceiling systems for residential, commercial and institutional projects.</p>
        <a href="/contact" class="btn btn-primary">Request a Consultation</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  /* Product Hero */
  .product-hero {
    background: #f8f9fa;
    padding: 5rem 0;
  }

  .hero-layout {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1.3fr;
    gap: 3rem;
    align-items: center;
  }

  .hero-image {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
  }

  .hero-image img {
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 420px;
    height: auto;
  }

  .section-label {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    color: #2061B7;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .hero-text h2 {
    font-size: 2.5rem;
    font-weight: 800;
    color: #0E2B47;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.1;
  }

  .hero-text > p {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    color: #444;
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  .three-layers {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 1.25rem;
  }

  .layer {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1rem;
    align-items: flex-start;
  }

  .layer-number {
    width: 36px;
    height: 36px;
    min-width: 36px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: #0E2B47;
    color: #fff;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    margin-top: 0.125rem;
  }

  .layer strong {
    display: block;
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: #0E2B47;
    margin-bottom: 0.25rem;
  }

  .layer p {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: #555;
    line-height: 1.5;
    margin: 0;
  }

  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .hero-layout {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 2rem;
    }

    .hero-image {
      order: -1;
    }

    .hero-text h2 {
      font-size: 2rem;
    }
  }

  /* Panel Close-Ups */
  .panel-closeups {
    background: #fff;
    padding: 5rem 0;
  }

  .closeup-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: 1.5rem;
  }

  .closeup-card {
    border-radius: 1rem;
    overflow: hidden;
    background: #f8f9fa;
    border: 1px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.06);
    transition: transform 0.3s ease, box-shadow 0.3s ease;
  }

  .closeup-card:hover {
    transform: translateY(-4px);
    box-shadow: 0 8px 32px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
  }

  .closeup-card img {
    width: 100%;
    height: 280px;
    object-fit: cover;
  }

  .closeup-text {
    padding: 1.5rem;
  }

  .closeup-text h3 {
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: #0E2B47;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .closeup-text p {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: #555;
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin: 0;
  }

  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .closeup-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 1.25rem;
    }
  }

  /* Why Ceiling */
  .why-ceiling-group {
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .diagonal-divider {
    line-height: 0;
  }

  .diagonal-divider svg {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: 80px;
    margin-bottom: -1px;
  }

  .why-ceiling {
    background: #0E2B47;
    padding: 5rem 0;
  }

  .why-layout {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 3rem;
    align-items: center;
  }

  .section-label--light {
    color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.6);
  }

  .why-text h2 {
    font-size: 2.25rem;
    font-weight: 800;
    color: #fff;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
    line-height: 1.15;
  }

  .why-text > p {
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.8);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .why-text > p strong {
    color: #fff;
  }

  .why-points {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    margin-top: 1.5rem;
  }

  .why-point {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }

  .why-point svg {
    width: 20px;
    height: 20px;
    min-width: 20px;
    color: #4ade80;
    margin-top: 0.15rem;
  }

  .why-point span {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.85);
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  .why-point strong {
    color: #fff;
  }

